    <name>
      <text>5.2.8 (Sin squared equation not exact)</text>
    </name>
    <questiontext format="moodle_auto_format">
      <text><![CDATA[<p>How many solutions to the equation {@eqn@} are there in the range \(0 < x < 360^\circ\)? </p>
<p>[[input:ans1]] [[validation:ans1]][[feedback:prt1]]</p> 
<p>What is the smallest solution in the given range? Give your answer to the nearest degree.</p>
<p>\(x = \) [[input:ans2]] [[validation:ans2]][[feedback:prt2]]</p>]]></text>
    </questiontext>
    <generalfeedback format="moodle_auto_format">
      <text><![CDATA[<p>Since we have {@eqn@} we see that \(\sin^2(x) = \frac{{@ang@}}{{@aa@}}\) therefore \(\sin x = \pm {@sqrtang@}\), therefore \(\sin x\) can be either positive or negative so we would expect to find a solution from all four quadrants. Therefore there are {@ta1@} such solutions in this case, corresponding to  the form \(x\) and \(180^\circ - x\), \(180^\circ + x\) and \(360^\circ - x\).</p>

<p>The solutions are:
\[
x = {@soln1@}, \: {@soln2@}, \: {@soln3@} \: {@soln4@}

\]In this case, the smallest solution in the range is \(x={@ta2@}\), which we can obtain from our calculator and then ordering the possibilities from each of the quadrants. </p>]]></text>
    </generalfeedback>
